# orcasecurity_integration_tines_template (Resource)

Manages a [Tines](https://www.tines.com/) integration in Orca Security.

Orca stores Tines as a webhook variant: under the hood this resource creates an
external service config of `service_name = "webhook"` with `type = "tines"`.
You could achieve the same result with `orcasecurity_integration_webhook_template`, but
the dedicated resource hides the webhook plumbing and mirrors how the Orca UI
displays the integration.

## Example Usage

### Basic example

{{tffile "examples/resources/orcasecurity_integration_tines_template/resource.tf"}}

### Sourcing the API key from HashiCorp Vault

```terraform
data "vault_generic_secret" "tines" {
  path = "secret/tines/orca"
}

resource "orcasecurity_integration_tines_template" "from_vault" {
  template_name = "tines-prod"
  webhook_url   = "https://your-tenant.tines.com/webhook/<path>/<secret>"
  api_key       = data.vault_generic_secret.tines.data["api_key"]
}
```

## Argument Reference

* `template_name` — (Required, String) Identifier for the integration as shown
  in the Orca UI. Changing this forces a new resource.
* `webhook_url` — (Required, String) Tines webhook URL Orca posts events to.
* `api_key` — (Required, String, Sensitive) Tines API key sent with each
  request.
* `body_fields` — (Optional, List of String) Optional list of Orca alert fields
  to include in the request body.
* `custom_headers` — (Optional, Map of List of Object) Optional custom HTTP
  headers, keyed by header name. Each value is a list of
  `{ custom = "<value>" }` objects so a single header name can carry multiple
  values.
* `is_enabled` — (Optional, Bool) Defaults to `true`.
* `is_default` — (Optional, Bool) Defaults to `false`.
* `business_units` — (Optional, Set of String) Optional set of Orca business
  unit IDs that may use this integration.

## Attribute Reference

* `id` — (String) Orca external service config identifier (UUID).

## Notes

* `api_key` lives inside the JSON config (not in SSM), so Orca's GET response
  includes it. The provider still marks it as `sensitive = true` to keep it
  out of CLI output and never overwrites the planned value during Create or
  Update.
* Use an encrypted remote backend (S3 + KMS, GCS, Terraform Cloud, etc.) and
  restrict read access to the state.

## Import

```bash
terraform import orcasecurity_integration_tines_template.example tines_name
```
